Plot replicate correlations

Kaelan (1028-02098-001-001)

May 03, 2023

1. Introduction

The goal of this analysis is to plot replicate correlations for all genomics data sets used in this study. This markdown includs ChIP-nexus, ATAC-seq, ChIP-seq, and MNase-seq, included in various time points and/or mutants. Note that these replicate correlation plots will encompass various supplemental figures to show high data quality.

4.3. Plot correlation plots

library(ggrastr)

# Define plotting function

plot_cor<- function(peaks, signal1 = signal1, signal2 = signal2, name = name, colour = colour){
  x <- ggplot(as.data.frame(peaks), aes(log(signal1+1), log(signal2+1)))+ 
  #geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "dotted") + 
  #geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dotted") + 
  geom_point_rast(colour = colour, size = 0.2)+
  #geom_hex(bins = 100) +
  ggtitle(name) +
  xlab("Log(Replicate 1 + 1)") +
  ylab("Log(Replicate 2 + 1)") +
  stat_cor(method="pearson") +
  theme_cowplot()
  
  x

}

# Read in Excel table that contains a copy of the correlation values calculated above

library(readxl)

rep_corr_r.df <- readxl::read_xlsx(path="/l/Zeitlinger/ZeitlingerLab/Manuscripts/Zelda_and_Nucleosomes/Analysis/analysis/xlsx/rep_corr_df.xlsx", ) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

rep_corr_summary.plot <- ggplot(rep_corr_r.df, aes(x=comparison)) +
  geom_tile(aes(y=state, fill=r)) +
  geom_text(aes(y=state, label=r)) +
  facet_wrap(exp_type ~ condition, scales = "free_y") +
  scale_fill_viridis(limits = c(0,1), breaks = c(0, .2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1), begin = 0, end = .92) +
  theme_cowplot()

rep_corr_summary.plot
